      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Bad",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "koenig-heading",
        "tag": "h3",
        "version": 1,
        "renderVersion": "4.0"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "There are lots of aspects of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Dual Souls",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", that while not necessarily bad, are really disappointing. The most glaring disappointment is the repetition, the bane of the fighting genre’s existence. This is an issue that most fighting games have, so it’s not unexpected nor will it deter many fighting purists but in a game like this that relies on the fun of the pace, variety is vital. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The fast pace of this game is a double edged sword; while I do think it makes the game more fun, it also makes the burnout from the aforementioned repetition happen even faster. I had a lot of fun with this game for about half an hour before I felt like I could put it down and never think about it again. It’s a weird thing to note because without the fast pace of the gameplay, it would drag and ultimately be unremarkable, but its presence also serves to make the game less engaging in the long run. I’ve never played a game that contradicts its own interests as severely as this one. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "It’s unfortunate and frustrating that the spartan nature of this game doesn’t allow for more than the bare minimum outside of the core content. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
